  "diary": "Woke up to another scorcher—91 degrees by afternoon. The bus ride to U-District felt longer than usual, but I needed the quiet before the morning rush hit. Vivace was packed; we were pulling shots non-stop, and I spent half the shift helping Maya dial in the grinder. My break was just me, iced tea, and a dog-eared copy of *Piranesi* at the counter.\n\nAfter work, I took that detour through Beacon Hill I've been meaning to explore—nothing fancy, just different angles on familiar streets. The Safeway run was quick, and then home to the rooftop. My tomatoes are finally getting serious about ripening. The heat was intense up there, but the basil smelled incredible after watering.\n\nCooked with what I'd grown, which always feels like small magic. Spent the evening bottling kombucha, tasting notes, prepping the next batch. There's something meditative about fermentation—watching tiny organisms do their work while I do mine. Felt grounded.",
  "thought_process": "The heat made everything feel slower, more deliberate. I skipped the concert at Gas Works—the smoke from BC wildfires had the air quality sketchy, and honestly, after managing people all morning, I needed quiet. My priorities shifted toward what I could control: the garden, the kombucha, the food I make with my hands. Work was steady but demanding, so I leaned into the ritual of my evening—the rooftop, the fermentation, the journaling. It's how I process. The detour home was intentional too; I'm trying to see my neighborhood differently, less as a place I rush through and more as something worth exploring. By bedtime, I felt purposeful rather than just tired.",
